      <h1 class="article-title">Shan Tuyet: Vietnam's Ancient Tea Legacy in Every Sip</h1>
      <p class="article-subtitle">High in the mist-shrouded Hoang Lien Son mountains of northern Vietnam, ancient Shan Tuyet tea trees have stood for over 300 years. These wild-grown, snow-kissed leaves produce a tea of extraordinary complexity — floral, honeyed, and lingering with a pristine mountain freshness that industrial plantations cannot replicate.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="feature-image">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558160074-4d7d8bdf4256?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=1200" alt="Ancient Shan Tuyet tea trees growing wild in the misty mountains of Ha Giang, Vietnam" loading="eager" decoding="async" width="1200" height="675" />
    </div>

    <div class="article-body">
      <p class="lead">Vietnam has a tea history stretching back over 2,000 years, long before the modern tea industry arrived. Hidden in the remote northern highlands, ancient Shan Tuyet (Snow Shan) tea trees — some over 300 years old — continue to produce leaves prized for their depth, purity, and unmatched natural sweetness. Greenie Vietnam brings this heritage directly from the H'Mong and Dao ethnic minority communities to importers, specialty tea brands, and distributors worldwide.</p>

      <h2>Where the Clouds Touch the Earth</h2>
      <p>Shan Tuyet tea grows at elevations of 1,000 to 1,800 meters in the Hoang Lien Son mountain range, where temperatures drop dramatically at night and clouds blanket the slopes by morning. These conditions create a unique stress response in the tea trees.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p><strong>Technical Note:</strong> High-altitude stress triggers increased polyphenol production (35–42% catechins), resulting in a tea with remarkable antioxidant properties and a complex, layered flavor profile unmatched by lowland varieties.</p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>These are not rows of manicured tea bushes. Shan Tuyet trees grow wild — gnarled trunks rising 5 to 15 meters, their leaves dusted with fine white hairs (the "snow" of their name) that shimmer silver under the highland sun. Each tree is an individual, shaped by centuries of wind, rain, and mountain soil.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>These trees were ancient when my grandfather's grandfather was a child. We do not own them — we are their caretakers.</p>
        <footer>— Elder Sung A Sinh, H'Mong tea custodian, Ha Giang</footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2 class="accent-green">Flavor Profile</h2>

      <figure class="image-float-right">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1563911892437-1feda0179e1b?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=600" alt="H'Mong artisan hand-rolling Shan Tuyet tea leaves" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>H'Mong artisan hand-rolling leaves — a technique passed through generations that preserves the leaf's cellular structure.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>The first steep releases a pale golden liquor with a fragrance of wild mountain flowers and honey. On the palate, the tea is remarkably smooth — no astringency, no bitterness — just a clean, sweet character that lingers long after the cup is empty. Subsequent infusions reveal deeper layers: hints of dried apricot, whispers of pine resin, and a cool minerality that recalls the mountain streams of its origin.</p>

      <p>Each sip of Shan Tuyet carries the pristine character of its highland home. The unique microclimate produces leaves with an exceptional concentration of aromatic compounds that reveal themselves across multiple infusions.</p>
