      <h3>The Harvest</h3>

      <h4 class="accent-green">I. Wild-Grown, Never Planted</h4>
      <p>Shan Tuyet trees propagate naturally through seed dispersal by birds and mountain winds. No pesticides, no fertilizers — these trees have thrived for centuries on the mountain's own terms.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">II. Hand-Picked by Ethnic Minority Communities</h4>
      <p>Harvesting requires climbing these massive trees by hand. H'Mong and Dao Red farmers select only the bud and the first two leaves — the "one bud, two leaves" standard that ensures optimal flavor concentration.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">III. Traditional Withering and Rolling</h4>
      <p>Leaves are withered on bamboo trays in mountain sunlight, then hand-rolled by artisans who have practiced this craft since childhood. The rolling breaks cell walls just enough to initiate controlled oxidation while preserving the leaf's structural integrity.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">IV. Low-Temperature Drying</h4>
      <p>Final drying over wood charcoal at precisely controlled temperatures locks in the tea's aromatic compounds while reducing moisture to below 5% — critical for shelf stability without preservatives.</p>

      <h2 class="accent-green">The Centuries-Old Flavor</h2>
      <p>Shan Tuyet is unlike any tea you've tasted. The first steep reveals a pale golden liquor with floral aromatics reminiscent of wild orchids and acacia honey. The second steep unfolds deeper complexity — stone fruit, gentle pine, and a lingering mineral finish that speaks of its high-altitude terroir. By the fifth steep, you discover hidden notes of dried apricot and a whisper of smokiness from traditional charcoal finishing.</p>

